  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I do vibrato on violin?",
  "response": "Vibrato on the violin is a technique that adds expression and warmth to your playing by oscillating the pitch of a note. It involves a controlled, rhythmic movement of the finger on the string. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you develop vibrato:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Ensure Proper Setup**\n- **Hand Position**: Your left hand should be relaxed and in the correct position. The wrist should be straight, and the thumb should lightly rest on the neck.\n- **Finger Placement**: Use the pad of your fingertip (not the tip) to press the string firmly but not too tightly.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Types of Vibrato**\nThere are three main types of vibrato on the violin:\n- **Wrist Vibrato**: The most common type, where the wrist moves back and forth.\n- **Arm Vibrato**: The entire forearm moves, creating a wider oscillation.\n- **Finger Vibrato**: The fingertip moves, producing a narrow oscillation (less common).\n\nStart with wrist vibrato as it\u2019s the easiest to master.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Basic Steps for Wrist Vibrato**\n1. **Anchor the Finger**: Press a note on the string (e.g., first finger on the D string).\n2. **Relax the Wrist**: Ensure your wrist is loose and not stiff.\n3. **Backward Motion**: Gently roll your wrist backward (toward the scroll), which slightly lowers the pitch.\n4. **Forward Motion**: Roll your wrist forward (toward the bridge), returning to the original pitch.\n5. **Repeat Smoothly**: Practice this motion slowly and smoothly, gradually speeding up as you gain control.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Practice Exercises**\n- **Without the Bow**: Practice the new motion on each finger without bowing to focus on the movement.\n- **Slow and Controlled**: Start slowly, ensuring the motion is even and controlled.\n- **Use a Metronome**: Practice vibrato in time with a metronome to develop consistency (e.g., one oscillation per beat).\n- **Scales and Long Notes**: Apply vibrato to long notes in scales or open strings to build muscle memory.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Common Mistakes to Avoid**\n- **Tension**: Keep your hand, wrist, and arm relaxed. Tension can make the vibrato stiff.\n- **Inconsistent Motion**: Ensure the oscillation is even and smooth.\n- **Overdoing It**: Avoid excessive vibrato that distorts the pitch or sounds uncontrolled.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Gradually Increase Speed**\n- Start with a wide, slow vibrato to understand the motion.\n- Gradually narrow the width and increase the speed as you gain confidence.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Listen and Adjust**\n- Pay attention to the sound. Vibrato should enhance the note, not overshadow it.\n- Experiment with different widths and speeds to match the musical context.\n\n---\n\nVibrato takes time and patience to master, so practice regularly and be consistent. With time, it will become natural and add depth to your playing!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
